{
  "texts": [
    "The number of nodes in each sub-graph is limited to a specified maximum, and so some edges for high degree nodes may be omitted, but they may be re-introduced from neighbouring nodes when the subgraphs are merged.",
    "The union of the sub-graphs forms the final graph, with cycles and weaker arcs being eliminated.",
    "FGES-Merge was found to be more accurate than all but one of the other BN structure learning algorithms evaluated in the DREAM5 gene network modelling challenge (Marbach et al. 2012).",
    "Madigan et al. (1996) noted that MCMC sampling over DAG space may be inefficient since DAGs in the same equivalence class have the same posterior probability, and instead proposed using Metropolis-Hastings sampling over equivalence classes.",
    "In this case, the proposal distribution must include one and two edge changes so that the chain is irreducible and can therefore sample the whole equivalence class space."
  ]
}